After a long week of hearings, I went on The Vergecast this week (https://w=
ww.theverge.com/2018/4/13/17206282/vergecast-podcast-zuckerberg-testifies-s=
potify-hardware-leak-huawei-p20-pro) to talk at length about Mark Zuckerber=
g's testimony. One topic we dug into was the Facebook CEO's repeated invoca=
tion of artificial intelligence as an eventual solution to many of the comp=
any's problems. As AI improves, Zuckerberg says, Facebook will more quickly=
 and accurately identify bad actors, and bad posts, and purge them from the=
 system.

Zuckerberg mentioned AI 33 times over 10 hours of hearings this week. Here =
he is=C2=A0talking to the House on Wednesday (https://www.washingtonpost.co=
m/news/the-switch/wp/2018/04/11/transcript-of-zuckerbergs-appearance-before=
-house-committee/?utm_term=3D.e74449d71c79):

We need to rely on and build sophisticated A.I. tools that can help us flag=
 certain content. And we're getting good in certain areas. One of the areas=
 that I mentioned earlier was terrorist content, for example, where we now =
have A.I. systems that can identify and =E2=80=94 and take down 99 percent =
of the al-Qaeda and ISIS-related content in our system before someone =E2=
=80=94 a human even flags it to us. I think we need to do more of that.It's=
 an appealing idea, at least to Facebook, where it promises to ward off reg=
ulation while preserving the company's profit margins. (It &quot;scales,&qu=
ot; in other words.) But AI brings pitfalls of its own, argues Jessica Less=
in: it has a terrible time explaining its actions, making it highly vulnera=
ble to charges of bias, and it can't process new kinds of threats, making i=
t ineffective during an ever-changing information war. Lessin writes (https=
://www.theinformation.com/articles/facebook-in-2020-the-ai-made-us-do-it?sh=
ared=3D5459de):

Imagine Zuckerberg telling a senator that a controversial post was mistaken=
ly pulled because the AI found it offensive=E2=80=94but then not being able=
 to explain why. The ammunition for those who want to prove Facebook is sys=
tematically biased could be endless.There's a third reason it's strange to =
invoke AI as a kind of magic talisman in this moment: the underlying machin=
e-learning technology is arguably responsible for some of the most pressing=
 problems in social media. It's &quot;AI,&quot; after all, that powers the =
News Feed, which continues to promote viral hoaxes and misinformation aroun=
d the world. Recommendation algorithms, which use machine-learning techniqu=
es to understand our interests and serve us fresh posts, have wreaked havoc=
 =E2=80=94 and the issue goes far beyond Facebook.

Here's Renee DiResta on a night spent browsing Pinterest (https://www.wired=
.com/story/creating-ethical-recommendation-engines/):

When a recent disinformation research project led me to a Pinterest board o=
f anti-Islamic memes, one night of clicking through those pins=E2=80=94crea=
ted by fake personas affiliated with the Internet Research Agency=E2=80=94t=
urned my feed upside down. My babies-and-recipes experience morphed into a =
strange mish-mash of videos of Dinesh D=E2=80=99Souza, a controversial righ=
t-wing commentator, and Russian-language craft projects.And here's Craig Si=
