ttps://www.buzzfeed.com/craigsilverman/youtube-channel-recommendations-alex=
-jones-radicalize?utm_term=3D.niyrE3OPz#.njkEJYxXb):

In one example, a user starting on a large mainstream channel such as TEDx =
ended up being suggested the channel of conspiracy theorist Alex Jones afte=
r just three steps of recommendations. In this case, the recommendations on=
 the TEDx channels page listed CNN, which in turn suggested Fox News, which=
 led to Alex Jones.Kaiser and Rauchfleisch found that channels with little =
or no political content, such as one that creates video remixes and mashups=
, saw the algorithm suggest conspiracy channels like Jones' and accused Hol=
ocaust-denier Styxhexenhammer666.=C2=A0DiResta continues:

Today, recommendation engines are perhaps the biggest threat to societal co=
hesion on the internet=E2=80=94and, as a result, one of the biggest threats=
 to societal cohesion in the offline world, too. The recommendation engines=
 we engage with are broken in ways that have grave consequences: amplified =
conspiracy theories, gamified news, nonsense infiltrating mainstream discou=
rse, misinformed voters. Recommendation engines have become The Great Polar=
izer.I'm not being a nihilist here =E2=80=94 machine-learning techniques al=
ready help keep terrorism and other bad stuff off the internet, and I'm sur=
e they will improve. But it feels a little glib to hold up AI as a savior w=
aiting in the wings while it causes actual harm in the meantime =E2=80=94 s=
omething tech executives are generally loath to discuss.

Still, it seemed to serve its purpose this week, writes my colleague Sarah =
Jeong (https://www.theverge.com/2018/4/13/17235042/facebook-mark-zuckerberg=
-ai-artificial-intelligence-excuse-congress-hearings?utm_campaign=3Dtheverg=
e&amp;amp;utm_content=3Dchorus&amp;amp;utm_medium=3Dsocial&amp;amp;utm_sour=
ce=3Dtwitter), who calls Zuckerberg's use of AI &quot;a dodge deployed on a=
 group of laypeople who, for the most part, regrettably swallowed it part a=
nd parcel.&quot;

&quot;The point isn=E2=80=99t just that Facebook has failed to scale for co=
ntent moderation. It=E2=80=99s failed to detect entire categories of bad be=
havior to look out for =E2=80=94=C2=A0like intentional misinformation campa=
igns conducted by nation-states, the spread of false reports (whether by na=
tion-states or mere profiteers), and data leaks like the Cambridge Analytic=
a scandal. It=E2=80=99s failed to be transparent about its moderation decis=
ions even when these decisions are driven by human intelligence. It=E2=80=
=99s failed to deal with its increasing importance in the media ecosystem, =
it=E2=80=99s failed to safeguard users=E2=80=99 privacy, it=E2=80=99s faile=
d to anticipate its role in the Myanmar genocide, and it=E2=80=99s possible=
 it=E2=80=99s even failed to safeguard American democracy.Artificial intell=
igence cannot solve the problem of not knowing what the hell you=E2=80=99re=
 doing and not really caring one way or the other. It=E2=80=99s not a solut=
ion for shortsightedness and lack of transparency. It=E2=80=99s an excuse t=
hat deflects from the question itself: whether and how to regulate Facebook=
.=C2=A0AI will surely do a lot of good in the years to come. But if they're=
 going to tout its promise, the platforms ought to reflect more on the bad =
it's doing already.=C2=A0


